Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

The dataset is a collected data for doctor appointments and associated characteristics including if the patient show-up or no-show the appointment and some other factors.

It contains 110.527 medical appointments (Rows) and 14 of features (Columns).

Columns Description¶

(PatientId, AppointmentID, Gender, ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay, Age, Neighbourhood, Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap, SMS_received, No-show).

1- PatientId: Shows the id of the patient

2- AppointmentID: Shows the id of the appointment

3- Gender: Shows the gender of the patient

4- ScheduledDay: Shows the day that the patient set up the appointment

5- AppointmentDay: Shows the day of the appointment

6- Age: Shows the age of the patient

7- Neighbourhood: Shows the neighbourhood of the hospital

8- Scholarship: Indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program 'Bolsa Famlia'

9- Hipertension: Does the patient have it or not

10- Diabetes: Does the patient have it or not

11- Alcoholism: Does the patient have it or not

12- Handcap: Does the patient have a Handcap or not

13- SMS_received: Does the patient received an SMS or not

14- No-show: Does the patient attended the appointment or not

Questions for Analysis¶

  • How much are the missed appointments from both genders?
  • Who is the most ages that didn't attends appointments and vice versa?
  • What is the most busy hours that the patients scheduled an appointments at?
  • How much the total of patient's attendence and non-attendence, and the different between them?
  • What is the most locations that have most patients attendnce and non-attendence, and vice versa?
  • Does receiving or not receiving SMS affects the patients attendence?
  • What is the most diasesses that the patients have?

In [93]:
 """
Python function that calculate the percentage of attendance and non-attendance.
    
returns:
dict: a dictionary with the percentage of attendance and non-attendance.
"""
def calculate_attendance_percentage(df, column, category):
    subset_df = df[df[column] == category]
    total_count = len(subset_df)
    attendance_counts = subset_df['attendance'].value_counts()
    percentage_dict = {
        'Attendance': (attendance_counts['yes'] / total_count) * 100,
        'Non-attendance': (attendance_counts['no'] / total_count) * 100  }
    return percentage_dict

gender_percentage = calculate_attendance_percentage(df, 'gender', 'F')
print("Attendance Percentage for Females:")
print(gender_percentage)

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, after analyzing this data regarding patient appointments in Brazilian hospitals, it showed us valuable information that could lead officials to make the appropriate decision. This report contains an analysis and presentation of charts using pandas, matplotlip and numpy. The charts and their types vary from one question to another. After I finished all this, it became clear that Brazilian women do not attend their hospital appointments more than men do, and as for the ages of patients, it does not affect attendance significantly, as I imagined that the elderly are the most absent from appointments, but it appeared that children under one year are the most absent. Perhaps due to the negligence of their families. The busiest time of day for booking appointments is 7 a.m., as I inferred from the data. The hospital, which is located in the JARDIM CAMBURI neighborhood, is the most absentee at appointments and also the most present at appointments. I thought that receiving text messages from patients would contribute to an increase in their attendance at appointments, but this does not seem to be the case, because the percentage varies and is not clear. The most common disease that Brazilian patients suffer from is hypertension.

Limitaions¶

Data Representativeness: The dataset utilized in this analysis represents a specific subset of appointments in Brazilian hospitals. It is essential to note that this dataset might not comprehensively reflect the characteristics of the entire population or encompass variations in healthcare practices across different regions or hospitals. If there was an extra columns of patients informations, the analysis will be wide and comprehinsive.

Limited Scope of Questions: The analysis addresses specific questions based on the available data. It might not cover all possible aspects related to patient attendance, and there could be additional questions or dimensions worth exploring.

Duplicates: There was 48,000+ duplicated values for the column 'PatientId', but I decided to drop it.
